Turkey Expands Diplomatic Horizons
Long before Turkey became a member of the European Union, the European powers nested the desire to penetrate the interior of this country.
In the eastern part of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps into Asia, lies one of the most interesting relics of disastrous imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in neo-renaissance style.
At least, this is what the guides say.
The building is set at the end of the platforms and carries in front two towers, one for each corner, all resembling a typical German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The building in your complex is a bit decaying.
But once the vaulted locker was over, there is no doubt what the grandeur of the company was that this was the westernmost door.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a “latecomer” in the imperial game, had the ambition to dominate the Middle East through this railroad that cured to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
However, the ambitions of this imperial Germany failed during World War I.
Its railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
Because of the relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen frontiers of the Cold War, it fell under
When the forces advanced into Egypt, they pushed the Turks and their German ally out of Palestine and Syria.
The news was also bad for the Hyderpasha station.
In 1917 an ammunition train exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources said it was sabotage.
Since then the station has decayed and remained on the sidelines of history.
But today, this railway, the gateway to Anatolia and all the eastern centres, serves - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's willingness to broaden its diplomatic horizons.
The Justice and Development Party in the government - the AKP - has planned a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
There is now a new policy of collaboration.
The Turkish government maintains excellent relations with Israel and Syria, with both the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
To assess the parameters of this new foreign policy, I got on a bunk and went to the Turkish capital Ankara, in order to visit one of the leaders of the AKP, an expert in foreign policy, the Turkish Prime Minister Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a trip of jolts, which produced the cadences of the ancient world in the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived at the Turkish capital - new city, designed to rule a new secular state, far from the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its clear Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This has aroused some suspicion in the West and especially in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern stone and steel structure - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by medium-built shopping malls and "power pastries" where middle-class managers in business suits - men and women - meet early in the morning to agree/do business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a center-right politician of almost any party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he still has a Blackberry.
“The goal of the party’s foreign policy is to re-integrate Turkey into its immediate vicinity.
The Cold War was an anomaly,” he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off in relations with its interior.
Today you have to look east and west at the same time.
It is not a case if it is not towards one or the other.
You have to do both.
“But surely at some point,” I ask, “Could Turkey be forced to choose?”
"Turkey," he replies, "does not want to offend that choice."
He then underlines a point that almost everyone I have spoken to so far has recited to me almost in memory: Turkey's relations not only with the Middle East, but with the Caucasus region, and with the entire Black Sea, represent a benefit for Europe and the United States as well as for Turkey itself.
The message seems to be: with Turkey on board, Europe in its complex can metaphorically mount those rail lines that open the world to East Asia and the Middle East.
Once again at Hydarpasha station, after a second sleepless night, my thoughts go back to the two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had attended the construction of this building 100 years ago.
How surprised would they have been to know that Europe’s ambitions in the Middle East, in large part, would be in Turkey’s hands today?
And waiting at the terminal the ferry that will take me back across the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was considered "the sick man of Europe."
So, there is not much doubt on which continent this fascinating country must claim.
