Morgan Stanley lost 6.79% to $23.07 each at 17:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to bank holding status,” said Juan Mack, the group’s chief executive officer.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which would have to allow him to diversify his activities but he passes under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces Wall Street’s biggest names to behave much more cautiously than before.
The modalities presented last Monday also show that the deal has been modified over the past few days: Last Monday, Morgan announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to Japan for almost $8.5 billion.
“A week ago,” Toshihide Mizuno, MUFG’s chief executive, explained in Tokyo, “we thought the participation would have been composed only of ordinary shares.
But in view of the current situation of the economy and the market, we have wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves. "
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below its book value.
And the operation will result in a dilution of about 20% of profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred securities into common stock within one year if they are sold at more than 50% above the conversion price, i.e. at $47 or so, over a given period.
Morgan Stanley says MUFG’s capital will enable it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokeswoman for the group declined, however, to give clarification on the strategic projects of the two new allies.
