The governments of the Netherlands nationalize a part of Fortis Bank.
The states of the Netherlands - being the first in Europe - will help with a nationalization of the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis that is in trouble due to the effect of the mortgage crisis of the North American market: the three countries will support in total with 11.2 billion euros this financial and insurance institution that also has business in Hungary.
This weekend, the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held higher-level consultations with the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission’s Head of Economic Competition.
Fortis Bank is the first to suffer the eurozone crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has been taking place in several waves more than a year ago, so the decisions taken with respect to the Bank, in a sense, can be considered as precedents.
According to the decision taken early on Sunday, the three states will buy about half (49 percent) of the Bank’s property in their area.
The Bank will certainly sell a part of its business, including mainly the activities -mainly insurance - bought last year by the Dutch ABN Amró.
Fortis shares began a sharp decline last week and for the second half of the week there were already significant signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees this bank is too large to allow it to go bankrupt.
The company's shares declined 12 percent on Friday alone, the lowest in 14 years.
Since January, the value of shares has declined by more than two-thirds.
Looking at current stock prices, the total value of the group’s capital in the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company’s executives this is not real.
The Bank’s management blamed the sharp drop in Fortis shares on the insecurities of the U.S. market in relation to the approval of the $700 billion U.S. package plan.
On Monday, the shares showed a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank’s new CEO.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has made a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured investors that they didn’t have to worry, they won’t lose their money.
There has been no panic among the Bank’s clients so far, they have not invaded the bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also purchased leasing companies.
Fox in the chicken coop
In the United States, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract when they see drug purchase data.
Privacy policy specialists fear that the personal data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are programs for the protection of personal data, which to the use of the data of the prescriptions in all cases binds it to the approval of the given person.
It must be in independent hands, because otherwise, "we trust the chicken coop to the fox" - quotes the Washington Post to Richard Dick, designer of the medical prescriptions follow-up program.
Insurance companies make the price of insurance and the amount of compensation depend on the customer’s health status and if they believe the risk is excessive, they simply don’t make the contract.
Before they sent the client to medical control and signed the contract with him already knowing the result of the control.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer identification number he easily gets from pharmacies the list of medications bought in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the client's illnesses and health status.
For example, if you consistently take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that the blood fat level is practically incurably high, so you are immediately included in a higher risk category.
Numerous versions of the program circulate, some even establish a number of risks, so the insurance company in addition to the administration has hardly anything to do, although there are small difficulties about it.
Among the disadvantages of the program is for example that some drugs are multi-purpose, for example certain substances serve both to treat headaches and for heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is an important risk factor for insurance companies while the former does not.
Special companies were formed to consult and process these data, which before acquiring the necessary information from the pharmacies, request the approval of the patient.
The authorities are already forcing them to do so, although they have not received a fine for negligence so far.
Some companies have also been developing laboratory test results and combining them with drug consumption data to provide more accurate information about the patient’s health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and at the same time it is increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those that provide health services.
The bill that gives the right to the authority to control specialized companies for the provision of personal data is already before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: therefore he developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the individual for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another matter that such a person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the hens, in spite of everything, are exposed to the good will of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union doubles its trade with India
As the European Union and India are reciprocal trading partners, this issue, in addition to the other mostly global problems, dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today, to deal mainly with nuclear energy cooperation.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a major developing democratic power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs, the member countries have not yet been able to come up with a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue has not been addressed at the ninth summit that began yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, the president of the European Union, José Manuel Barroso, the president of the European Commission and Javier Solana, the main representative of foreign policy, welcomed Manmohan Singh, the prime minister of India, with whom they reached an agreement to double in five years, i.e. increase their trade to more than 100 billion euros.
Given that between 2000 and 2007 the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious target.
Thus, the existing twenty-six bilateral civil aviation agreements with India were legally harmonized, so that air transport could also fly in the future.
India until the end of 2009 wants to sign the free trade agreement with the Union.
Sarkozy promised to speed up negotiations.
The goal is balance, because while the EU is India’s first trading partner, New Delhi is only ranked ninth among the EU’s trading partners.
The summit focused its attention on global issues.
Both sides condemned the Afghan and Pakistani situation and terrorism - all forms of the latter - and urged the convening of a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha trade liberalization round was also pressed, although both sides bear great responsibility for its failure.
The EU has confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate programme, that is, by 2020 it wants to reduce polluting emissions by at least twenty percent.
India also agrees with this, just as next year’s climate conference should reach a global agreement and reduce production of greenhouse gases by 50 percent by 2050.
They also wished to hinder rising food prices and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today the head of government of India will travel to the French capital, where - in a bilateral meeting - he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Paris is confident that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency reports, the agreement would be for a period of 15 years.
