Steve Fossett's plane found missing a year ago
The remains of the plane of Steve Fossett, the missing millionaire on September 3, 2007, have been found while flying over the Nevada desert.
The debris has been found on an altiplano at an altitude of 3,000 meters, in the area of the Nevada Mountains of Mammoth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, there were no human remains.
"The plane has been located, we have sent a squadron, and now we have it confirmed that it is proper to what Steve Fossett was flying over on the day of his disappearance," he said in a print conference.
The commissioner said no human remains were found either on the plane or in the vicinity.
The 63-year-old millionaire was reported dead in February.
The U.S. Office of Transportation Safety (NTSB) has reported that a few hours after the sighting of the wreckage, a team of investigators has been sent to identify the device: it is the Bellanca 8kcab, dispersed since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, always in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett’s personal remains have been found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents with the name Fossett, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweatshirt.
Fossett's search had been interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The millionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of firsts.
In 2002, on the sixth attempt, he had become the first Man to complete the spin of the world in a hot air balloon: two lonely weeks of flight.
Three years later, he had made the round of the world by plane and without stopovers.
Among his records, also that for having flown at 15,445 meters in height, over the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
